          "body": "Between God's silent action (8:1-5) and God's explicit command (8:15-17), Noah undertakes a methodical reconnaissance. He opens the window after forty days (8:6), sends a raven (8:7), then sends a dove on three successive seven-day cycles (8:8-12). The reconnaissance is neither impatient nor passive. Noah uses the means available to him — the birds — to read the state of the world while he waits for God's word. The contrast between the raven and the dove is theologically rich, even if we must not over-allegorize it. The raven (a scavenger, Levitically unclean per Leviticus 11:15) flies back and forth without returning — it finds enough in the post-flood wreckage to sustain itself. The dove (ritually clean, associated with sacrifice) can find no resting place in a world still covered with water; it returns to Noah, who reaches out his hand and brings it back into the ark. The dove's inability to rest in the ruined world, and its return to the hand that shelters it, is a picture of the soul that finds no resting place in the world as it currently stands and returns to the one who has preserved it. The progressive reports — no olive leaf, olive leaf, no return — chart the restoration of the earth across three weeks, one sign at a time. This is how God often reveals His working: incrementally, one signal at a time, requiring patient trust between each signal."
