          "title": "The first act of the new world — an altar (8:20)",
          "body": "Noah's first act on dry ground is to build an altar and offer burnt offerings (olah) from every clean animal and bird. The burnt offering was the most costly of Israel's later sacrificial system — nothing was reserved for the offerer; everything was wholly consumed. Noah takes from the very animals God preserved through the flood — the clean animals he was commanded to bring in sevens (7:2-3) — and offers them back to God before a single field is plowed, a single house is built, or a single seed is planted. This is worship that precedes provision. John Calvin (Commentary on Genesis) observed that Noah's altar is the first explicitly named altar in the Bible — and it is built not inside a temple, not in a designated sacred precinct, but on the bare earth of the emerging world. The priority is theological: the new world begins with sacrifice, with the acknowledgment that survival itself is gift, and that the Giver is owed the first and best. The parallels with the NT are precise. Jesus Christ, the antitype of Noah (Matthew 24:37-39; 1 Peter 3:20-22; 2 Peter 2:5), is Himself the burnt offering wholly given — nothing held back. The 'soothing aroma' God smells in 8:21 is the language Paul uses of Christ's sacrifice in Ephesians 5:2: 'an offering and a sacrifice to God as a fragrant aroma.' Noah's altar points forward to the altar of the cross."
