        "excerpt": "Then he sent out a dove from him, to see if the water was abated from the face of the land.",
        "body": "The chapter's first half is a study in divine patience made visible through meticulous dating and progressive disclosure. The narrator records seven distinct time-markers across 8:3-12: 150 days (8:3), the 17th day of the 7th month (8:4), the 1st day of the 10th month (8:5), the end of 40 days (8:6), then three seven-day intervals (8:8-12). This density of chronological precision is unparalleled in Genesis up to this point. The narrator is insisting on the historicity of the events while simultaneously encoding a theological message: God's restoration of the world is not rushed. It proceeds at the pace He sets, not at the pace anxiety demands.\n\nNoah's bird-reconnaissance (8:6-12) operates within the space between God's silent action and God's spoken word. Noah does not remain entirely passive — he actively seeks to read the state of creation through available means. The raven is sent first (8:7), a bird that can feed on carrion and floating debris; it returns no report. Then the dove is sent three times. The first returns empty (8:9). The second returns with a freshly-plucked olive leaf (8:11). The third does not return (8:12). This three-stage disclosure pattern — nothing, a sign, full absence — is the biblical pedagogy of progressive revelation: God rarely gives the complete picture at once. He gives enough to sustain trust for the next seven days, then enough to confirm the trend, then the full release.\n\nThe detail of Noah reaching out his hand to receive the returning dove (8:9) is small but significant. The same hand that built the ark (6:14-16) now reaches out in tenderness to shelter a bird that found no rest. The dove's inability to rest in the still-flooded world and its return to Noah's hand is the chapter's most intimate image — and it functions typologically. Peter Davids, writing on 1 Peter 3:20-22, notes that the flood narrative's typological function in the NT depends precisely on the ark as a place of shelter and rest for those who have no rest outside it. The dove's return is the animal world's embodiment of that truth.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yonah* (dove) — the same word as the prophet Jonah's name, itself rich with imagery of one sent out and returning from the deep. *Manoach* (resting place, 8:9) — rest, settlement; the same root as Noah's name (*noach*). The dove sought what Noah represents: rest, settledness, a resting place in a world where none yet exists."
