        "excerpt": "Then Noah built an altar to the LORD, and took of every clean animal and of every clean bird and offered burnt offerings on the altar.",
        "body": "The first recorded altar in the Bible is built not by a priest, not inside a sacred space, not after long deliberation — but immediately, on bare earth, by a man who has just stepped off a boat. Noah builds the altar before anything else — before shelter, before farming, before the covenant of chapter 9. The sequence is programmatic: worship precedes provision. The new world's foundation is not agriculture or governance or family structure; it is sacrifice.\n\nNoah takes from the clean animals and birds — the very creatures brought in seven pairs precisely for this purpose (7:2-3). The burnt offering (olah, 'that which goes up') was the most comprehensive sacrifice in Israel's later sacrificial system: the entire animal was consumed on the altar, nothing reserved for the offerer or the priests. Everything given, nothing held back. The cost is real — these clean animals are the seed stock for the earth's repopulation. Noah offers from scarcity, not surplus. This is the widow's mite of the Old Testament.\n\nThe altar is also the chapter's first use of the covenant name YHWH (translated LORD in NASB). The transition from Elohim (God as cosmic sovereign, used in 8:1-17) to YHWH (God as covenant-keeper, used in 8:20-21) is precise and deliberate. Noah is not merely acknowledging a cosmic power; he is worshiping the covenant God — the God who remembered him, the God whose name is bound to promise. John Calvin, commenting on 8:20, observed: 'Noah did not offer sacrifice from a vague notion of religion, but from faith; and that faith rested on the word of God.' Worship that rests on the word is worship that God receives.\n\nThe typological dimension is explicit in the New Testament. Ephesians 5:2 describes Christ's sacrifice as 'a fragrant aroma' — the identical language of 8:21's 'soothing aroma.' Noah's burnt offering is a type of the offering that God would Himself provide (22:8): the Lamb who is wholly given, nothing reserved, whose sacrifice is the true aroma that moves God to make a covenant of mercy with a humanity that has not improved.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mizbeach* (altar) — from *zavach*, to slaughter; the place of slaughter-sacrifice. *Olah* — the burnt offering; from *alah*, to go up; what rises to God. *Nichoach* (soothing, pleasing) — the same descriptor used of Christ's sacrifice in Ephesians 5:2 (LXX *euōdia* / Hebrew *reach nichoach*). The connection is not coincidental; Paul is drawing on the Genesis 8 vocabulary to describe the cross."
